{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486790"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:44:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:44:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"175"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/175"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.13,0.01,0.07,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"175"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77221"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/175"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"175"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62728"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"226"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"2249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2253"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"137"},{"type":"contributions","id":"231"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7691"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77221"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of worsening shortness of breath and productive cough. He has a medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His regular medications include salbutamol inhaler, fluticasone/salmeterol inhaler, and tiotropium inhaler. He is an ex-smoker with a 40 pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears fatigued but responsive. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 86% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He is speaking in short sentences. There is widespread expiratory wheeze and crackles in the right mid and lower zones. Metabolic flap is present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter receiving antibiotics, nebulised bronchodilators, hydrocortisone, and oxygen via venturi mask, his arterial blood gas reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.28 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpaO2 60 mmHg (75-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpaCO2 65 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3 26 mmol/L (22-28)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continuous positive airway pressure","Nasal high flow oxygen","Chest drain","Intubation and ventilation","Bilevel positive airway pressure"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an acute exacerbation of COPD complicated by type 2 respiratory failure (hypoxemia and hypercapnia). The arterial blood gas shows uncompensated respiratory acidosis with elevated paCO2, normal bicarbonate, and low pH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilevel positive airway pressure\u003C/strong\u003E (BPAP) is the most appropriate next step. BPAP provides two levels of pressure support - higher during inspiration and lower during expiration - which reduces work of breathing and improves ventilation. Multiple studies have shown BPAP reduces mortality and intubation rates in COPD patients with hypercapnic respiratory failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous positive airway pressure\u003C/strong\u003E (CPAP) provides only a single pressure level which, while helpful for oxygenation by keeping airways open, does not provide the same ventilatory support as BPAP. The dual pressure levels in BPAP make it more comfortable and effective for COPD patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasal high flow oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E would improve oxygenation but would not address the ventilatory failure. Additionally, high flow oxygen could be dangerous in this COPD patient as it may worsen CO2 retention by removing hypoxic respiratory drive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntubation and ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if the patient deteriorates despite BPAP, develops respiratory arrest, or cannot tolerate non-invasive ventilation. It is not first-line therapy given the risks and complications associated with invasive ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest drain\u003C/strong\u003E insertion would only be appropriate if there was evidence of pleural effusion or pneumothorax, neither of which are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bilevel positive airway pressure (BPAP) is the preferred mode of non-invasive ventilation for hypercapnic respiratory failure in COPD exacerbations.","BPAP reduces work of breathing and mortality compared to other oxygen delivery methods in acute COPD exacerbations with type 2 respiratory failure.","Uncompensated respiratory acidosis is characterised by elevated paCO2, normal bicarbonate, and low pH."],"references":["Yang IA, Brown JL, George J, Jenkins S, McDonald CF, McDonald V, Smith B, Zwar N, Dabscheck E. The COPD-X Plan: Australian and New Zealand Guidelines for the management of Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease 2020. Available at: https://copdx.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/COPDX-V2.62-June_Oct-2020-PUBLISHED.pdf","Osadnik CR, Tee VS, Carson-Chahhoud KV, Picot J, Wedzicha JA, Smith BJ. Non-invasive ventilation for people with respiratory failure due to exacerbation of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). Cochrane reviews. 2017; CD004104. Available at: https://www.cochrane.org/CD004104/AIRWAYS_non-invasive-ventilation-people-respiratory-failure-due-exacerbation-chronic-obstructive-pulmonary","Baudouin S, Blumenthal S, Cooper B et al. British Thoracic Society Standards of Care Committee. Non-invasive ventilation in acute respiratory failure. Thorax. 2002; 57:192-211. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11867822/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62728"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"175"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62728"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T13:16:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T13:16:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"175"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77221"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","s